SIMPLE: stage
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stage
<hw>Stage</hw> <pr>(st⟦amac⟧j)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>estage</ets>, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧tage</ets>, (assumed) LL.
<ets>staticum</ets>, from L. <ets>stare</ets> to stand. See
<er>Stand</er>, and cf. <er>Static</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A floor
or story of a house.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Wyclif.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An elevated platform on which an orator may speak, a
play be performed, an exhibition be presented, or the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A floor elevated for the convenience of mechanical
work, or the like; a scaffold; a staging.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A platform, often floating, serving as a kind of
wharf.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The floor for scenic performances; hence, the
theater; the playhouse; hence, also, the profession of representing
dramatic compositions; the drama, as acted or exhibited.</def> <-- stars
of stage and screen -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Knights, squires, and steeds, must enter on the
<qex>stage</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lo! where the <qex>stage</qex>, the poor, degraded
<qex>stage</qex>,⟦br⟧
Holds its warped mirror to a gaping age.</q> <rj><qau>C.
Sprague.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A place where anything is publicly exhibited; the
scene of any noted action or career; the spot where any remarkable
affair occurs; <as>as, politicians must live their lives on the public
<ex>stage</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>When we are born, we cry that we are come⟦br⟧
To this great <qex>stage</qex> of fools.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Music and ethereal mirth⟦br⟧
Wherewith the <qex>stage</qex> of air and earth did ring.</q>
<rj><qau>Miton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>The platform of a microscope, upon which an object
is placed to be viewed. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of
<er>Microscope</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A place of rest on a regularly traveled road; a
stage house; a station; a place appointed for a relay of
horses.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>A degree of advancement in a journey; one of several
portions into which a road or course is marked off; the distance between
two places of rest on a road; <as>as, a <ex>stage</ex> of ten
miles</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>stage</qex> . . . signifies a certain distance on a
road.</q> <rj><qau>Jeffrey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He traveled by gig, with his wife, his favorite horse performing
the journey by easy <qex>stages</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Smiles.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>A degree of advancement in any pursuit, or of
progress toward an end or result.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such a polity is suited only to a particular <qex>stage</qex> in
the progress of society.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>A large vehicle running from station to station for
the accommodation of the public; a stagecoach; an omnibus.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧A parcel sent you by the <xex>stage</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj> <mark>[Obsolescent]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I went in the sixpenny <qex>stage</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>One of several marked phases or
periods in the development and growth of many animals and plants;
<as>as, the larval <ex>stage</ex>; pupa <ex>stage</ex>; zoea
<ex>stage</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stage box</b></col>, <cd>a box close to the stage in a
theater.</cd> -- <col><b>Stage carriage</b></col>, <cd>a
stagecoach.</cd> -- <col><b>Stage door</b></col>, <cd>the actors' and
workmen's entrance to a theater.</cd> -- <col><b>Stage lights</b></col>,
<cd>the lights by which the stage in a theater is illuminated.</cd> --
<col><b>Stage micrometer</b></col>, <cd>a graduated device applied to
the stage of a microscope for measuring the size of an object.</cd> --
<col><b>Stage wagon</b></col>, <cd>a wagon which runs between two places
for conveying passengers or goods.</cd> -- <col><b>Stage
whisper</b></col>, <cd>a loud whisper, as by an actor in a theater,
supposed, for dramatic effect, to be unheard by one or more of his
fellow actors, yet audible to the audience; an aside.</cd></cs> <--
<col><b>stage of the game</b></col>, [Colloq.] stage n. 10. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stage</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stage
<hw>Stage</hw> <pr>(st⟦amac⟧j)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To exhibit
upon a stage, or as upon a stage; to display publicly.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stagecoach</ent>⟦br⟧
